00:39:23.310 --> 00:39:26.310
So the first one
is along the lines

00:39:26.310 --> 00:39:29.140
of telling real from fake.

00:39:29.140 --> 00:39:32.879
So I don't do the kind of
really spectacular science demos

00:39:32.879 --> 00:39:33.920
that people sometimes do.

00:39:33.920 --> 00:39:37.520
So I try to have some
kind of relevance to them.

00:39:37.520 --> 00:39:39.190
And this one is
practical advice on how

00:39:39.190 --> 00:39:41.520
to tell real silk
from fake silk.

00:39:41.520 --> 00:39:45.510
It turns out that fake silk
is actually incredibly good

00:39:45.510 --> 00:39:46.080
these days.

00:39:46.080 --> 00:39:49.560
And even experts can't
really reliably tell

00:39:49.560 --> 00:39:54.310
just by feeling it
whether it's real or not.

00:39:54.310 --> 00:39:58.200
Because there's enough variation
in what real silk is like.

00:39:58.200 --> 00:40:00.190
And the imitations
are good enough

00:40:00.190 --> 00:40:02.460
that you need a better way.

00:40:02.460 --> 00:40:04.960
And obviously, you can do
chemical analyses or whatever.

00:40:04.960 --> 00:40:06.670
But there's a much
simpler way, which

00:40:06.670 --> 00:40:08.860
is to simply burn a bit of it.

00:40:08.860 --> 00:40:10.820
And apparently, if
you're a silk buyer

00:40:10.820 --> 00:40:15.300
and you're evaluating
something, that's how you do it,

00:40:15.300 --> 00:40:16.670
is you take a lighter along.

00:40:16.670 --> 00:40:18.710
And you pull a little
thread out of the garment,

00:40:18.710 --> 00:40:19.530
and you light it.

00:40:19.530 --> 00:40:21.060
And so I read about
this, and I was

00:40:21.060 --> 00:40:25.180
thinking it sounds pretty clear,
but how does it really look?

00:40:25.180 --> 00:40:27.680
And so I'll give you now
a practical demonstration

00:40:27.680 --> 00:40:30.960
of how you tell what
it actually looks like.

00:40:30.960 --> 00:40:35.860
And thank you, Simon,
for this fine torch.

00:40:35.860 --> 00:40:37.500
So you burn it,
and if it's silk--

00:40:37.500 --> 00:40:39.700
you see how it kind of melts?

00:40:39.700 --> 00:40:42.290
It actually pulls
back a little bit,

00:40:42.290 --> 00:40:46.352
but then it always puts
itself out-- eventually.

00:40:46.352 --> 00:40:48.310
And this is the point
where we'll all find out.

00:40:48.310 --> 00:40:53.050
And it leaves a char behind.

00:40:53.050 --> 00:40:54.980
There's a black
char, and it smells

00:40:54.980 --> 00:40:59.180
of burning hair--
terrible smell.

00:40:59.180 --> 00:40:59.740
Synthetic.

00:40:59.740 --> 00:41:02.260
So this is, I believe
this is nylon.

00:41:02.260 --> 00:41:03.190
It feels really nice.

00:41:03.190 --> 00:41:05.920
It's a beautiful rope.

00:41:05.920 --> 00:41:07.790
Now when you burn
this-- and this will

00:41:07.790 --> 00:41:12.710
be true of any synthetic
imitation silk-- first of all,

00:41:12.710 --> 00:41:15.620
it melts much more.

00:41:15.620 --> 00:41:22.030
And when it does eventually
catch fire-- yeah,

00:41:22.030 --> 00:41:25.640
that is absolutely
diagnostic of fake silk, when

00:41:25.640 --> 00:41:29.580
you have the dripping flaming
balls of death falling down.

00:41:32.200 --> 00:41:34.920
That's not silk.

00:41:34.920 --> 00:41:36.377
But it's also much
more attractive

00:41:36.377 --> 00:41:37.460
really in a darkened room.

00:41:37.460 --> 00:41:39.510
That's kind of fun.

00:41:42.675 --> 00:41:44.175
Oh, oh, and right,
and you can hear.

00:41:44.175 --> 00:41:45.591
I don't know if
