00:42:13.470 --> 00:42:16.180
There's a whole section of lots
of different fibers burning,

00:42:16.180 --> 00:42:18.880
and it's quite
attractive, the ways

00:42:18.880 --> 00:42:20.780
in which different
types of fibers burn.

00:42:20.780 --> 00:42:23.000
Some of them burn
very differently.

00:42:23.000 --> 00:42:26.330
Cotton balls burn in
a very beautiful way.

00:42:26.330 --> 00:42:28.440
Kevlar doesn't burn at all.

00:42:28.440 --> 00:42:31.360
And then, of course, there's the
whole natural versus synthetic.

00:42:31.360 --> 00:42:35.170
But one of the more
surprising things that burns

00:42:35.170 --> 00:42:37.490
is actually steel wool.

00:42:37.490 --> 00:42:41.140
You might not think of
steel or iron as flammable.

00:42:41.140 --> 00:42:43.860
And normally it isn't,
but only because normally,

00:42:43.860 --> 00:42:46.530
when you have some of it,
it's a big chunk of it

00:42:46.530 --> 00:42:51.210
with a substantial volume
versus surface area.

00:42:51.210 --> 00:42:53.730
But if you have fine
steel wool like this,

00:42:53.730 --> 00:42:55.897
it has very little volume
and a lot of surface area.

00:42:55.897 --> 00:42:58.396
And it turns out it's actually--
and we should at this point

00:42:58.396 --> 00:43:00.335
turn off the lights,
if that's possible.

