00:49:11.860 --> 00:49:14.910
AUDIENCE: So I work on Chrome,
and I'm a little bit biased

00:49:14.910 --> 00:49:18.964
on people building native
apps versus for iOS or Android

00:49:18.964 --> 00:49:20.130
or something versus the web.

00:49:20.130 --> 00:49:22.596
And obviously, you got
started a few years ago

00:49:22.596 --> 00:49:24.970
when the web couldn't do as
many things as it can do now.

00:49:24.970 --> 00:49:27.240
I was wondering if
you could talk nerdily

00:49:27.240 --> 00:49:29.454
a little bit about why
you just have an iOS

00:49:29.454 --> 00:49:31.620
app versus an Android app,
and whether or not you've

00:49:31.620 --> 00:49:33.995
looked at being able to do
some of this stuff on the web,

00:49:33.995 --> 00:49:35.570
because your apps are amazing.

00:49:35.570 --> 00:49:37.153
THEODORE GRAY: That's
a good question.

00:49:37.153 --> 00:49:41.590
And I mean, so the "Elements"
app and the "Molecules" app,

00:49:41.590 --> 00:49:44.270
with the exception of the
molecular dynamic simulation,

00:49:44.270 --> 00:49:48.690
is-- you could do that
as an HTML5 thing.

00:49:48.690 --> 00:49:51.915
I mean, being able to spin--
I think five years ago when

00:49:51.915 --> 00:49:54.700
we did it, it was
probably not really going

00:49:54.700 --> 00:49:56.202
to be super smooth
as a web thing.

00:49:56.202 --> 00:49:57.910
It probably could be
done as a web thing.

00:49:57.910 --> 00:50:03.600
But many of the apps that
we do have a lot more stuff

00:50:03.600 --> 00:50:06.467
that you can't really do as
a web app sort of a thing.

00:50:06.467 --> 00:50:08.175
I don't know how you
exactly describe it,

00:50:08.175 --> 00:50:11.500
but you need your fingers on
the hardware a little more.

00:50:11.500 --> 00:50:12.450
You need performance.

00:50:12.450 --> 00:50:16.300
You need access to
bits of the hardware

00:50:16.300 --> 00:50:19.360
that you can't necessarily get
to through a web interface.

00:50:19.360 --> 00:50:24.420
And we're in the business
of publishing apps

00:50:24.420 --> 00:50:26.430
to make money on the
sales of the apps, which

00:50:26.430 --> 00:50:27.940
is a really tough
business to be in.

00:50:27.940 --> 00:50:32.480
I think it's gotten worse
and worse over time.

00:50:32.480 --> 00:50:36.250
So the "Elements" app
just-- we've sold,

00:50:36.250 --> 00:50:41.040
I think, 360,000 copies,
something like that, at $14

00:50:41.040 --> 00:50:42.010
a copy.

00:50:42.010 --> 00:50:44.990
And that's very
unusual for apps.

00:50:44.990 --> 00:50:47.760
It's like apps don't cost $14.

00:50:47.760 --> 00:50:51.610
And if they do, they don't
sell in those sort of numbers.

00:50:51.610 --> 00:50:56.535
And that's our
best-selling app to date.

00:50:56.535 --> 00:50:57.410
That's our first app.

00:50:57.410 --> 00:50:59.160
It's the one that got
the company started.

00:50:59.160 --> 00:51:01.360
We've had a few other apps
that have been successful

00:51:01.360 --> 00:51:03.030
at those price points.

00:51:03.030 --> 00:51:07.280
"Disney Animated" has done
reasonably well at $10 a copy.

00:51:07.280 --> 00:51:10.590
We make these super
premium, lush--

00:51:10.590 --> 00:51:13.600
they're like the app equivalent
of a coffee table book.

00:51:13.600 --> 00:51:16.040
And it's very
difficult to get people

00:51:16.040 --> 00:51:21.000
to consider the concept of
paying actual money, let alone

00:51:21.000 --> 00:51:23.600
like $10, for an app--
the exact same people

00:51:23.600 --> 00:51:26.170
who would not bat an
eye at paying $20 or $30

00:51:26.170 --> 00:51:33.110
for a print book or even $10 for
an ebook, just a regular ebook

00:51:33.110 --> 00:51:35.390
on their Kindle, with no
pictures or anything, just

00:51:35.390 --> 00:51:36.620
plain text.

00:51:36.620 --> 00:51:39.950
People are more willing to
spend $10 on a plain text ebook,

00:51:39.950 --> 00:51:43.477
than they are on the
same text in an app.

00:51:43.477 --> 00:51:45.560
There was a great example
that some book-- not one

00:51:45.560 --> 00:51:48.360
of ours-- but a book that
came out simultaneously

00:51:48.360 --> 00:51:55.620
in print, as a static ebook, as
an audio book, and as an app.

00:51:55.620 --> 00:51:58.170
The app, of course,
included everything

00:51:58.170 --> 00:51:59.650
that all the other
versions had--

00:51:59.650 --> 00:52:02.850
the full text and the
recording and plus lots

00:52:02.850 --> 00:52:04.050
of other interactivity.

00:52:04.050 --> 00:52:06.390
And, of course, the app
was by far the cheapest.

00:52:06.390 --> 00:52:09.370
The audio book was
the most expensive,

00:52:09.370 --> 00:52:10.810
and the ebook was in between.

00:52:13.330 --> 00:52:15.100
And that makes no sense.

00:52:15.100 --> 00:52:21.990
It's entirely the psychological
environment of the app store.

00:52:21.990 --> 00:52:24.290
And that's unfortunately a
place where the Android app

00:52:24.290 --> 00:52:28.080
store is even worse
than the iOS app store.

00:52:28.080 --> 00:52:32.540
The iOS app store started out,
and particularly for iPad apps,

00:52:32.540 --> 00:52:34.060
supporting a
reasonably high price

00:52:34.060 --> 00:52:37.510
point for people who wanted to
make money by actually selling

00:52:37.510 --> 00:52:39.566
the apps, as opposed
to many people

00:52:39.566 --> 00:52:40.940
who make apps who
have completely

00:52:40.940 --> 00:52:43.290
different ways of making
money or who are just

00:52:43.290 --> 00:52:48.765
going for the viral hit and can
make by with a few cents a user

00:52:48.765 --> 00:52:51.310
or something.

00:52:51.310 --> 00:52:53.880
And every time we try to think
about doing this for Android--

00:52:53.880 --> 00:52:56.340
and it's not that we have
anything against Android.

00:52:56.340 --> 00:52:58.870
It's just we have
X amount of money

00:52:58.870 --> 00:53:01.280
to put into developing
our next app.

00:53:01.280 --> 00:53:06.126
And if we do this for iOS,
we have some expectation

00:53:06.126 --> 00:53:07.500
of what we're
going to make back.

00:53:07.500 --> 00:53:09.300
We have one platform to target.

00:53:09.300 --> 00:53:11.050
Well, all right, two
or three or whatever.

00:53:11.050 --> 00:53:12.674
But they're all very
nicely integrated.

00:53:12.674 --> 00:53:13.659
They all-- it works.

00:53:13.659 --> 00:53:15.450
We look at Android,
it's like first of all,

00:53:15.450 --> 00:53:16.730
forget all the
phones, because people

00:53:16.730 --> 00:53:17.771
don't use this on phones.

00:53:17.771 --> 00:53:20.860
So you're talking
about tablets only.

00:53:20.860 --> 00:53:22.780
It's fragmentation.

00:53:22.780 --> 00:53:23.920
It's maintenance.

00:53:23.920 --> 00:53:25.720
The development costs
are much higher.

00:53:25.720 --> 00:53:30.367
And the store is not one that is
conducive to high-priced apps.

00:53:30.367 --> 00:53:32.200
And so we always just
say no, you know what?

00:53:32.200 --> 00:53:33.885
Let's make another iOS app.

00:53:33.885 --> 00:53:36.420
And I wish it weren't so.

00:53:36.420 --> 00:53:40.460
And I wish we could do something
that would be cross-platform

00:53:40.460 --> 00:53:43.380
as a web thing, but
when you're doing

00:53:43.380 --> 00:53:46.870
synchronized audio,
complex interactivity

00:53:46.870 --> 00:53:49.560
with multiple streams
of audio and things

00:53:49.560 --> 00:53:52.780
and video-- our
apps are very big.

00:53:52.780 --> 00:53:56.885
They're like a gigabyte
or more sometimes.

00:53:56.885 --> 00:53:59.260
It's like there's only one
platform where that really

00:53:59.260 --> 00:53:59.790
make sense.

00:53:59.790 --> 00:54:03.280
And that's, unfortunately,
right now iOS.

00:54:03.280 --> 00:54:06.089
And I think it's like the
days are numbered where we're

00:54:06.089 --> 00:54:08.130
going to keep doing this,
because the returns are

00:54:08.130 --> 00:54:11.200
actually not improving,
despite the number of devices,

00:54:11.200 --> 00:54:15.470
because the app store
environment is deteriorating.

00:54:15.470 --> 00:54:17.660
AUDIENCE: What inspired
you to get into chemistry

00:54:17.660 --> 00:54:18.887
and stay in chemistry?

00:54:18.887 --> 00:54:21.470
THEODORE GRAY: Well, actually I
was never really in chemistry.

00:54:21.470 --> 00:54:24.270
So I have a bachelor's
degree in chemistry,

00:54:24.270 --> 00:54:27.330
and then I dropped out
of graduate school to go

00:54:27.330 --> 00:54:31.230
and co-found Wolfram Research
with Stephen Wolfram, which

00:54:31.230 --> 00:54:35.150
is the makers of Mathematica,
and ultimately, WolframAlpha.

00:54:35.150 --> 00:54:37.380
And so I spent the
last-- I mean, that

00:54:37.380 --> 00:54:41.050
was 1987-- and up until
a couple of years ago,

00:54:41.050 --> 00:54:43.130
that was kind of my job.

00:54:43.130 --> 00:54:47.640
And this whole periodic
table book-writing stuff

00:54:47.640 --> 00:54:49.940
was just a hobby.

00:54:49.940 --> 00:54:51.440
Since then, I've
now transitioned

00:54:51.440 --> 00:54:53.710
into Touch Press,
our map company,

00:54:53.710 --> 00:54:55.900
being my primary occupation.

00:54:55.900 --> 00:55:00.720
And since then, decided, OK, no,
I'm just going to be a writer

00:55:00.720 --> 00:55:02.620
and do this, because
this is much more

00:55:02.620 --> 00:55:07.730
interesting than working
on other people's projects.

00:55:07.730 --> 00:55:10.410
But as far as why
chemistry, I don't know.

00:55:10.410 --> 00:55:12.120
I like the names.

00:55:12.120 --> 00:55:15.200
I think organic chemical
naming systems are fascinating.

00:55:15.200 --> 00:55:19.485
That was my original reason for
studying organic chemistry--

00:55:19.485 --> 00:55:21.770
not a good basis
for a career choice.

00:55:21.770 --> 00:55:24.460
And then the reason I decided
to get out of chemistry

00:55:24.460 --> 00:55:27.336
was because I realized that if
I became a professional chemist,

00:55:27.336 --> 00:55:28.710
particularly an
academic chemist,

00:55:28.710 --> 00:55:30.300
I wouldn't get to
do any chemistry.

00:55:30.300 --> 00:55:32.771
But you know, I like blowing
stuff up and mixing things.

00:55:32.771 --> 00:55:35.270
And you can't do that if you're
a chemist, because you spend

00:55:35.270 --> 00:55:37.200
all your time writing
grant proposals.

00:55:37.200 --> 00:55:42.830
And being a science writer, like
for "Popular Science" column,

00:55:42.830 --> 00:55:46.150
every month, for 10 years,
I got to blow something up.

00:55:46.150 --> 00:55:47.550
They'd send a photographer down.

00:55:47.550 --> 00:55:48.720
I had a big shop.

00:55:48.720 --> 00:55:52.210
And we would do something
involving chemicals--

00:55:52.210 --> 00:55:53.614
build transparent
rocket engines.

00:55:53.614 --> 00:55:55.030
It's all this stuff
that you don't

00:55:55.030 --> 00:55:57.000
get to do if you're
actually a chemist.

00:55:57.000 --> 00:56:01.990
So my interest was primarily
nurtured and expanded

00:56:01.990 --> 00:56:05.520
by not actually being a chemist
in a professional sense,

00:56:05.520 --> 00:56:07.590
but getting to do
all the stuff that

00:56:07.590 --> 00:56:10.470
is the most fun
and the most useful

00:56:10.470 --> 00:56:14.004
in terms of communicating
chemistry to the public.

00:56:14.004 --> 00:56:16.420
I actually got an award from
the American Chemical Society

00:56:16.420 --> 00:56:19.350
called the Grady Stack Award
for Communication of Chemistry

00:56:19.350 --> 00:56:22.560
to the Public, which I
think of as the "We Found

00:56:22.560 --> 00:56:28.787
a Journalist Who Doesn't Hate
Us" award, which is hard.

00:56:28.787 --> 00:56:31.120
It's hard for them, and they
don't have a lot of choice,

00:56:31.120 --> 00:56:33.475
as evidenced by the fact
that they gave it to me.

00:56:33.475 --> 00:56:35.350
AUDIENCE: With all the
content that you have,

00:56:35.350 --> 00:56:37.330
have you ever considered
creating a MOOC

00:56:37.330 --> 00:56:40.080
to open chemistry to the masses?

00:56:40.080 --> 00:56:41.580
THEODORE GRAY: Funny
you should ask.

00:56:41.580 --> 00:56:42.510
Yes, I have thought about it.

00:56:42.510 --> 00:56:44.009
And I've also thought
about how much

00:56:44.009 --> 00:56:47.920
I enjoy not being a creator
of stuff that actually

00:56:47.920 --> 00:56:50.330
gets officially used in schools.

00:56:50.330 --> 00:56:50.830
Right?

00:56:50.830 --> 00:56:55.540
Because as soon as you do that,
there are so many restrictions,

00:56:55.540 --> 00:56:57.330
and there's so
much you can't do.

00:56:57.330 --> 00:56:59.560
Like my books will
find themselves

00:56:59.560 --> 00:57:02.225
in the library of
a grade school,

00:57:02.225 --> 00:57:03.835
if no parent has noticed.

00:57:06.692 --> 00:57:09.490
And it's like the more
enlightened parents get it

00:57:09.490 --> 00:57:13.245
for their kids, but it would
never, ever pass as a textbook.

00:57:13.245 --> 00:57:15.620
And I wouldn't want to have
to take everything out of it.

00:57:15.620 --> 00:57:17.536
Actually, in the case
of the "Molecules" book,

00:57:17.536 --> 00:57:22.020
I admit, OK, we sold so
many copies of "Elements"

00:57:22.020 --> 00:57:24.390
to the Scholastic book
fairs, where they go around

00:57:24.390 --> 00:57:27.065
to schools, and they have
these displays-- lots

00:57:27.065 --> 00:57:28.800
of copies every year.

00:57:28.800 --> 00:57:30.824
And so my publisher
was very eager

00:57:30.824 --> 00:57:32.990
that they should do the
same thing with "Molecules."

00:57:32.990 --> 00:57:34.950
And so they ran it by them.

00:57:34.950 --> 00:57:36.880
And there was this
woman who reminds

00:57:36.880 --> 00:57:42.090
me Dolores Umbridge from the
"Harry Potter" series, who

00:57:42.090 --> 00:57:44.540
went through it line by line.

00:57:44.540 --> 00:57:47.520
And we cut out-- you
know, there was some stuff

00:57:47.520 --> 00:57:49.770
that even I have to admit
after the fact was perhaps

00:57:49.770 --> 00:57:54.600
a bit off-color and maybe
not really belonging there.

00:57:54.600 --> 00:57:57.660
There was a marijuana
bud that was full-page.

00:57:57.660 --> 00:57:59.130
It was gorgeous.

00:57:59.130 --> 00:58:01.889
I mean it was just
unbelievably beautiful.

00:58:01.889 --> 00:58:03.680
And you can talk about
the fact that that's

00:58:03.680 --> 00:58:06.190
a pesticide to the plant.

00:58:06.190 --> 00:58:10.909
The THC is a pesticide
that the plant makes.

00:58:10.909 --> 00:58:12.450
But we took it out,
because it's just

00:58:12.450 --> 00:58:14.250
like, you don't
really need that.

00:58:14.250 --> 00:58:16.580
And we made the
heroin rock smaller.

00:58:16.580 --> 00:58:17.670
And it was gorgeous, too.

00:58:17.670 --> 00:58:19.420
It's a beautiful,
beautiful rock of heroin

00:58:19.420 --> 00:58:21.711
that I had to flush down the
toilet, because you really

00:58:21.711 --> 00:58:23.338
can't hang on to
that kind of thing.

00:58:23.338 --> 00:58:25.630
[LAUGHTER]

00:58:29.544 --> 00:58:30.710
Where was I going with this?

00:58:30.710 --> 00:58:31.251
I don't know.

00:58:31.251 --> 00:58:33.360
Yeah, so right, actually
being a textbook author

00:58:33.360 --> 00:58:35.120
isn't very appealing
because you don't

00:58:35.120 --> 00:58:36.390
get to do that kind of stuff.

00:58:36.390 --> 00:58:42.192
However, there's value in it
and watch this space perhaps.

00:58:42.192 --> 00:58:42.900
MALE SPEAKER: OK.

00:58:42.900 --> 00:58:45.358
Let's all thank Theo for coming
here and giving a super fun

00:58:45.358 --> 00:58:45.930
talk.

00:58:45.930 --> 00:58:48.980
[APPLAUSE]

